Limited-Overs cricket

  • An over is six balls, delivered by the same bowler.
  • T20, limited-overs format, game comprises of 20 overs per innings.
  • 11 players a side and a maximum of ten outs allowed a side.
  • Only two innings in a game, one for each side to bat.
  • Toss winning captain decides whether they bat or bowl first.
  • The team batting first sets the target, equal to their innings total plus one, for the other team to score to win.
    • E.g., if the first innings total is 149, the team batting second has to score 150 to win the game.

Motivation

  • Most of the (public) cricket stats are simple averages or proportions.

  • For limited-overs cricket, these statistics fall short of providing a comprehensive picture of a player‚Äôs performance and contribution to the team‚Äôs success.

  • Inspired by sabermetrics, we develop metrics such as

    • run value
    • runs above average
    • value over replacement/readily available player
    • wins above replacement

Batting avg = \(\frac{\text{runs scored}}{\text{no. of outs}}\)

Strike Rate = \(\frac{\text{runs scored * 100}}{\text{balls faced}}\)

Boundary Percent = \(\frac{\text{no. of boundaries hit}}{\text{balls faced}}\)

Balls per dismissal = \(\frac{\text{balls faced}}{\text{no. of outs}}\)

Bowling avg = \(\frac{\text{runs conceded}}{\text{no. of wikcets taken}}\)

Economy = \(\frac{\text{runs conceded}}{\text{overs bowled}}\)

Strike Rate = \(\frac{\text{balls bowled}}{\text{wikcets taken}}\)

cricWAR

Inspiration

Data: cricketdata R Pkg

  • Data sourced from ESPNCricInfo and cricsheet.

  • Arguably the most rich R pkg for cricket data with access to

    • ball-by-ball for different formats,
    • player play by team and innings, and
    • player meta data (DOB, batting/bowling hand, etc. )
  • Rob J Hyndman (Monash University) and students developed it in 2018.
    • Jacquie Tran (High performance Sport New Zealand) added the functionality to access ball-by-ball data from cricsheet.
    • Recently, I have contributed to further develop the functionality.

Expected Runs (ER)

  • On any given ball, a batter may
    • take a single (1 run), a double (2 runs), a triple (3 runs) by running between wickets (bases) or
    • hit a boundary which maybe a four (4 runs) or a six (6 runs).
  • We define the state of a limited-over game by the over (o), and the wickets lost/outs (w). The expected runs for a state \[ \theta(o,w) = \mathbb{E}[R ~| ~over = o, ~wicketsLost = w] \] where \(R\) is a random variable representing the runs scored on a ball.
  • E.g. \(\theta(4,0) = 1.6\) means in 4th over with no outs an average of 1.6 runs are scored per ball.
  • The value \(\theta(o,w)\) is estimated as the empirical average.

Run Value

  • We define the run value, \(\delta\), for a ball as \[ \delta = r - \theta\] where \(r\) is the actual runs scored on a ball and \(\theta\) is the expected runs.

  • E.g. \(\theta(4,0) = 1.6\) and the batter hits a six.

    • Batter obtains a run value of \(\delta = 6 - 1.6 = 4.4\)

Runs Conseravtion Framework

  • As described in openWAR, runs conseravtion framework dictates that

    • every run value \(\delta\) gained by batter on a ball

    • is accompanied by the bowler gaining \(- \delta\) for that ball.

The extras (wides and no-balls) are completely attributed to the bowler.

Fielding Restrictions Affect Scoring

  • Only a maximum of two fielders are allowed outside the 30-yard (inner) circle, For the first six overs (power play) of a T20 innings.
    • After powerplay (PP), a maximum of five players are allowed outside the inner circle.

  • Batters take advantage by hitting shots to cross the inner circle and score boundaries (4s or 6s). Aggressive batting during last few overs as well.

  • Players playing in different stages (PP, last overs, etc) can accumulate (or lose) run value quick and hinders the comparison of players across different playing positions.

Adjusting Run Values

  • The weighted average of expected runs \(\theta\), of all states, is evaluated and then \(\theta\) for each state is divided by this weighted average to get the Leverage Index (LI) for each state. \[ LI(o,w) = \frac{\theta(o,w)}{\frac{\sum_{{(o,w)}} n_{(o,w)}\theta(o,w)}{\sum_{(o,w)} n_{(o,w)}} }\] An LI of one corresponds to a state which is average wrt scoring rate, whereas a LI \(\gg\) 1 means it is a high scoring state, and a LI \(\ll\) 1 means it is a low scoring state.
  • The run value \(\delta\) is divided by the corresponding leverage index (LI) and labelled as leveraged run value

\[\delta^{lev} = \frac{\delta}{LI}\].

Batting Adjustments

  • There are different factors beyond the control of batters that affects the run values and makes it hard to compare them across contexts.
  • In particular, we want to account for the
    • venue,
    • platoon advantage (RH batter against LH bowler or vice-versa),
    • innings (first Vs second), and
    • the bowling pace (spin Vs pace).

We adjust for these factors using a linear regression \[ \delta^{lev}_i = \mathcal{B} X_i + \epsilon_i\] where \(X_i\) contains the indicator variables for the categorical features described above and \(\mathcal{B}\) represents the effects of these features.

Batting Adjustments

  • The estimated residuals from the regression

\[ \hat \epsilon_i = \delta^{lev}_i - \mathcal{\hat B} X_i \]

indicate the part of the leveraged run values \(\delta^{lev}_i\) that is not attributable to venue, innings, bowling pace, and platoon advantage.

  • We refer to \(\hat \epsilon_i\) as adjusted batting run values.

Bowling Adjustments

  • Similar to batting adjustments, we adjust the bowling run values for venue, innings, platoon advantage, and the bowling pace.

\[ -(\delta_i + \omega_i)^{lev} = \mathcal{A} X_i + \eta_i\]

where \(\omega_i\) represents extras (wides, noballs), \(X_i\) the features, and \(\mathcal{A}\) the affects of features on the run value.

  • We refer to \(\hat \eta_i\)

\[\hat \eta_i = -(\delta_i + \omega_i)^{lev} - \mathcal{\hat A} X_i\] as adjusted bowling run values.

Runs Above Average

  • To the best of our knowledge, the fielding tracking data is not available, at least publicly.
  • In the absence of fielding data, we accredit these adjusted batting and adjusted bowling run values to the batter and bowler, respectively.

\[ RAA^{bowl}_i = \hat \eta_i, ~~~ RAA^{bat}_i = \hat \epsilon_i \]

  • The runs above average for each ball a player played (batted or bowled), over a season, is summed to get the total measure of \(RAA_x\) for player \(p\), where \(I(\cdot)\) is the indicator function. \[ RAA_p = \sum_i RAA^{bat}_i \cdot I(batter = p) + RAA^{bowl}_i \cdot I(bowler = p) \]

Value over Replacement Player

  • We consider a roster-based replacement level approach.

  • We use the Indian Premier League (IPL), a T20 league, to illustrate the approach.

    • IPL teams have a minimum of 18 players and a maximum of 25 players on their squad.

    • On average, teams have played 19 distinct players each season over the last decade.

    • We analyzed the number of distinct batters and bowlers and how many matches they played.

  • We take the top 8ùëÅ batters and 8ùëÅ bowlers in regards to the playing time to be the league-level players, and the remaining players would be considered replacement-level players, where ùëÅ is the number of teams.

Value over Replacement Player

  • All the replacement level players are pooled together, and the average RAA per ball is evaluated, \(avg.RAA_{rep}\).

  • For every actual player p, we can associate a replacement-level shadow player with runs above average \[RAA_{rep} = B_p \cdot avg.RAA_{rep}\] where \(B_p\) is no. of balls played by player p.

    • This replacement-level shadow player provides a relevant baseline for comparison, specific to the player being considered.
  • Value over replacement player (VoRP) for a player p is evaluated as \[VoRP_p = RAA_p - RAA_{rep}\]

Wins above Replacement

Wins above replacement (WAR) for a player p is evaluated as \[ \text{WAR}_p = \dfrac{VoRP_p}{RPW} \]

  • Following the approach taken by nflWAR, we use linear regression to estimate runs per win (RPW) \[ W_i = \beta_0 + \beta ~ \text{Run Diff}_i + \epsilon_i\] where \(W_i\) is the team \(i's\) win total in a regular season and Run Diff\(_i\) is the run differential (run scored - run conceded) for team \(i\) in that regular season.

  • The estimate \(\hat \beta\) represents the increase in win total for each one unit increase in run differential of the team, meaning RPW can be estimated by \(1/\hat\beta\).

    • After fitting the model, we got \(RPW \approx \frac{1}{0.011839} = 84.5\).

Uncertainty Estimation

  • Sources of variability

    • Model estimation variability
    • Player outcome variability

  • Consider a player with fixed ability and repeat the same season for that player many times.

  • Following an approach similar to openWAR, we use a resampling strategy to generate distributions for each player‚Äôs RAA and WAR values.

    • For a particular season, we resample (with replacement) individual balls, fit the regression model for adjusting run values, and use the adjusted run values for new RAA and WAR values for individual players.
    • We present the uncertainty estimates with 1000 simulated seasons.

WAR Intervals

Metric Reliability

  • Discrimination: Does the metric reliably differentiate between players?
    • Useful for attribution, e.g. end of year awards: MVP, Player of the series, etc.
  • Stability: Does the metric measure a quantity that is stable over time?
    • Useful for player acquisition
  • Independence: Does the metric provide new information?

cricWAR Metric Reliability

Batters w min of 60 balls faced in IPL Regular Seasons

Players w min of 60 balls played in IPL Regular Seasons

  • Discrimination, \(\mathcal{D}_{sm} = 1 - \frac{E_{sm}[V_{spm}[X]]}{V_{sm}[X]}\), represents fraction of between-player variance in metric \(m\) (in season \(s\)) due to true difference in player ability

  • Stability, \(\mathcal{S}_{m} = 1 - \frac{E_{m}[V_{pm}[X] - V_{spm}[X]]}{V_{m}[X] - E_m[V_{spm}[X]]}\), represents a fraction of the total variance in metric \(m\), with sampling variability removed, that is due to within-player changes over time

Future Work

  • Pool data from different leagues and use a hierarchical model to estimate expected runs
    • Enough sample sizes available to use (over, ball in over, wickets) as the state.
  • Treat first and second innings separately.
    • For second innings, make use of required run rate in estimating run values.

    • runs above average
    • value over replacement/readily available player
